"""
# Enum Variant Lookup Across Struct/Enum Name Collision

**Feature IDs:** #INTERP-ENUM-GLOBAL-FALLBACK
**Category:** Interpreter
**Difficulty:** 2/5
**Status:** Regression

## Overview

Regression test for the interpreter semantic cascade that hard-failed with
`method 'X86_64' not found on type 'Architecture'` when an enum and a struct
share the same name across modules and only the struct is imported into the
caller's local namespace.

Specifically, `std.spec.arch` exports a `struct Architecture` and
`os.kernel.arch.arch_context` exports an `enum Architecture` with variants
`X86_64`, `Riscv64`, etc. When a spec imports `std.spec` (bringing the struct
into local `classes`) and then transitively calls a function that references
`Architecture.X86_64`, the interpreter's `Value::Constructor` branch falls
through to an enum-variant fallback. Before this fix the fallback only
consulted the module-local `enums` map and `BLOCK_SCOPED_ENUMS`, never the
cross-module `GLOBAL_ENUMS` registry — so the cross-module enum was invisible
and the test aborted with the bogus "method not found" error.

The fix (`src/compiler_rust/compiler/src/interpreter/expr/calls.rs`) adds
`GLOBAL_ENUMS` as a third probe in both the `Value::Constructor` static-method
fallback and the `Value::EnumType` variant-resolution path. This mirrors the
three-tier lookup already used in `interpreter_call/mod.rs`.

This spec exercises plain enum access (baseline) plus unit-variant access so
any regression that breaks `GLOBAL_ENUMS` chaining surfaces as a targeted
interpreter-unit failure rather than a distant system-spec cascade.
"""

import std.spec

enum TargetArch:
    X86_64
    Riscv64
    Arm64

describe "enum variant access via interpreter":
    it "resolves a unit variant on a top-level enum":
        val a = TargetArch.X86_64
        expect(a == TargetArch.X86_64).to_be_true()

    it "resolves a second variant to verify dispatch is not constant-folded":
        val a = TargetArch.Riscv64
        expect(a == TargetArch.Riscv64).to_be_true()
        expect(a == TargetArch.X86_64).to_be_false()

    it "round-trips through a function boundary":
        val a = echo_arch(TargetArch.Arm64)
        expect(a == TargetArch.Arm64).to_be_true()

fn echo_arch(a: TargetArch) -> TargetArch:
    return a
